OpenLaszlo server — compiler backend
====================================

The server compiles LZX→DHTML JS through a TS-FIRST, oracle-fallback backend.

Files
-----
  compiler/index.mjs   The adapter. compile(lzxAbsPath, {debug,lpsHome}) ->
                       {siteDir, base, hash, backend, tag, cached}. Tries the
                       byte-exact TypeScript compiler; falls back to the Java oracle.
  compiler/oracle.mjs  The Java 4.9 oracle path (relocated verbatim from the old
                       server/compile.mjs). The FALLBACK backend.
  server/compile.mjs   Thin re-export shim of compiler/index.mjs (so index.mjs's
                       `import { compile } from "./compile.mjs"` is unchanged).
  server/wrapper.mjs   renderWrapper({base,debug}) — generates the app index.html
                       (matches the oracle's post-rewrite wrapper, loads /runtime).
  server/.cache-ts/    The TS closure cache (compiled JS blob + dependency manifest
                       per (mainpath, props)). Busts on any tracked-dep change.
  server/.cache-ts-sites/  Assembled site dirs for the pure-TS path.
  server/.cache/       The oracle's site-dir cache (unchanged).

How a request is served
-----------------------
1. TS try (non-debug): compileFileCached() against the SAME LPS_HOME the harness uses,
   with proxied:false (SOLO, matching the oracle's DeploySOLODHTML output).
2. If the JS has NO sprite refs  -> PURE TS PATH: write <base>.lzx.js (TS output) +
   generated wrapper + the app's own assets. No Java.
3. If the JS HAS sprite refs     -> TS-js over oracle assets: the oracle builds the
   sprite montages + packed resources (cached), then <base>.lzx.js is overwritten with
   the byte-exact TS output. The SERVED JS is the TS output either way.
4. debug build / unsupported construct / oracle error -> full oracle fallback.

`backend` ("ts" | "oracle") is logged per compile (`[compiler] …`).

ETag / 304
----------
The TS path supplies a content tag (hash of the dependency closure). runApp() serves the
wrapper with `ETag: "<tag>"` and honors `If-None-Match` (-> 304). The oracle path has no
tag, so no ETag (graceful — those pages just don't conditional-GET).

Cache
-----
The TS path uses compileFileCached: an unchanged app serves from cache instantly; a
changed dependency (a component, an included lib, a resource — anything the compile read)
busts the cache and recompiles. The cache key includes a compiler-version fingerprint
(the dist build mtime), so rebuilding the compiler busts the cache automatically.

Gate
----
  node server/gate-served-parity.mjs
Proves the served <base>.lzx.js is byte-identical to the oracle output (after the harness's
appbuilddate/sprite normalization) on hello (pure TS) + calendar + dashboard (TS+assets),
and that a 2nd compile is a cache HIT and touching a dep INVALIDATES it. Exit 0 = pass.

Known sub-gap
-------------
Sprite-montage generation. The TS compiler references but does not PACK sprite-sheet PNGs,
so sprite-bearing apps still invoke the oracle to build the montages/resources (the served
JS is still the TS output). A TS sprite-packer would let those apps go fully Java-free.
